ecovery of literary works but also a major rethinking of literary history. In Since 1948, scholars consider how recent voices have succeeded older ones and reverberated in concert with them; how linguistic and geographical boundaries have blurred; how genres have shifted; and how canon and competition have shaped Israeli culture. Charting surprising trajectories of a vibrant, challenging, and dynamic literature, the contributors analyze texts composed in Hebrew, Yiddish, and Arabic; by Jews and non-Jews; and by Israelis abroad as well as writers in Israel. What emerges is a portrait of Israeli literature as neither minor nor regional, but rather as transnational, multilingual, and worthy of international attention.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aIsraeli literaturexHistory and criticism2DLC. 0aIsraeli literaturexHistory and criticism. 4aArea Studies : Israel Studies. 4aArea Studies : Middle East Studies. 4aJewish Studies : Jewish Studies. 4aLiterature : Literary Criticism. 4aLiterature : Literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Middle Eastern.2bisacsh1 aBerg, Nancy E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBerg, Nancy E., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDekel, Yael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGinsburg, Shai, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNotev, Eitan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPeleg, Yaron, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPinsker, Shachar, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRaizen, Michal, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSokoloff, Naomi B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSokoloff, Naomi B.